rves how anthropology operates as a technology of war. It tackles recent theories of humans in society colluding with imperialist claims, including anthropologists who have become  involved professionally in warfare through their knowledge of “cultures,” renamed as “human terrain systems.” The chapters link varied yet crucial domains of inquiry: from battlefields technologies, military-driven scientific policy, and economic warfare, to martyrdom cosmology shifts, media coverage of “distant” wars, and the virtualizing techniques and “war porn” soundtracks of the gaming industry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aTechnologyxAnthropological aspects. 0aWar and civilization. 0aWar and society. 0aWarxTechnological innovations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAbufarha, Nasser, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Robertson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerguson, R. Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinnström, Sverker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Roberto J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobben, Antonius C. G. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSluka, Jeffrey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStroeken, Koen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStroeken, Koen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSumera, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhitehead, Neil L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-201